{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e909fd95-49dc-451c-825e-f3ef655eec85","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` in the container\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### 5. Copy the trace out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, thread pool stats — useful to confirm the issue before collecting a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If the container image lacks the .NET SDK, you can use `dotnet-trace` from a **sidecar** or copy the global tool binaries in. On Windows containers, **PerfView** can also be copied in and run directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5d0e379a-eddb-4ac7-b3e2-5c15751dc22f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"980B:11A36E:CA2BF8:EAD7AF:69F4012A"},"id":"0cc0f021-d3aa-42fe-9a16-36899906b725","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:26:12.539Z","parentId":"f2a051c6-544e-494e-9fa2-b11e5b2f2635"}
